There's a bit going on here even though it's a small patch. I've left some comments inline.
Can you please make separate commits for each device type?
It has been seperated, thank you for the suggestion.

Can you please split this refactoring out to a separate commit also?

Further, isn't this adjusting the local type for another type on a DBus interface? I feel like that's sketchy territory, and the interface itself should be adjusted? Where's that change?
+1 Please separate the commit

It has been seperated, thank you for the suggestion.

As I know, dbus limit the most properties just can be got and tranformed from variant type.
In this case, the scale factor comes from entity-manager config, and was defined as "number", but before this change, the value was parsing into unsigned int which may cause error once 0 < value < 1.

Your commit message needs to refer to the interface definition for the field, the interface implementation, and also demonstrate the impact of the changes in the data presented on D-Bus (e.g. using `busctl`). What's currently written is not sufficient to evaluate whether this change is reasonable.

this customized scale factor declaration come from schemas as below:
https://github.com/openbmc/entity-manager/blob/0422a24bb6033605ce75479f675fedc76abb1167/schemas/legacy.json#L557C33-L557C33

like "CurrScaleFactor" for current using, "iout1_Scale" for iout using
They are declared as type of "number".
If there's a number 2.9 used in PSUsensor, it will lost the decimal part when trasform the value from variant to unsigned int and calculate to the wrong result.

for example, one sensor named "FANBOARD_ADC_48V_AUX_VOLT_V" set as below:
{
                "Address": 31,
                "Bus": 31,
                "Labels": [
                    "in6"
                ],
                "Name": "FANBOARD_ADC",
                "Type": "ADC128D818",
                "in6_Name": "FANBOARD_ADC_48V_AUX_VOLT_V",
                "in6_Scale": 31.9458,
            }

but scale factor in debug print is 31, not 31.9458:
Jul 28 22:50:36 bmc psusensor[788]: DEBUG_FACTOR:31, name:FANBOARD_ADC_48V_AUX_VOLT_V

The more reasonable way to resolve the problem is that using variant to float or double, as adc sensor doing so far:
https://github.com/openbmc/dbus-sensors/blob/436c5bdb25c775138c901dc707f203c076adcb97/src/ADCSensorMain.cpp#L237
Hi Delphine, I feel this change needs a more compelling argument regarding the interfaces involved.
Based on your description isn't this in-fact any non-integer value?

Exactly.
The commit message has been revised, thank you for the correction.

Okay, so the type in the EM interface is the type specified in the JSON configuration as inferred by nlohman::json. Which is kinda terrible. Oh well.

Separately, the expectation is you style your commit messages as described here:

https://tbaggery.com/2008/04/19/a-note-about-git-commit-messages.html

Please wrap the lines at appropriate widths.
Revised, thank you for the correction.
Can you please put this in a markdown code block and add some indenting to make it readable?
Revised, thank you for the correction.
Perhaps. I guess we're just trading-off where the quantisation occurs in the number space. Maybe it's more sensible that it happens at the extremes rather than around zero.
Would you help to tell if I should add any additional description?
Hi Delphine, I think I understand the issues now. I have a couple of small requests on the commit message.
you need more checks here.  Now that this is a double, you need to check that it's not NAN, is a valid value, etc.
Revised, thank you for correction.
Doesn't this now need to be std::powl now?  std::pow truncates.

Build failed with err "'powl' is not a member of 'std'"
std::pow will do overload with double as I surveyed
does this need to be changed?

This case seems isn't enteded when scale factor is customized (#887)
so I think that it's no need with this commit.
ACK

> This case seems isn't enteded when scale factor is customized 

I'm not sure I understand this.  You've changed the variable for BOTH customized scale and non-customized scale, so this likely needs changed, otherwise it will now truncate?

We are using customize cases only in yosemite4
is there any verification on your platform that side effect has occurred without this change?
Revised, thank your for correction
This doesn't seem right? Please delete this file.
Redundant patch has been removed, thank you for correction.

In theory negative scale factors are valid, right?

should this be != 0.0?
Revised, thank you for the correction.
These two checks are redundant.  std::isfinite is going to be all you need here.
Also, if we parse out a non-finite number, should we just log it, fail and continue to the next config?  Right now this code just accepts a default.

Revised, thank you for correction.

The failed case seems didn't changed with this commit, service will print error log, ignore the invalid value then continue to the next config, is there any additional action should be added as your expectation?

> The failed case seems didn't changed with this commit,

The failed case didn't exist before this commit.  Yes, I think we should log an error and continue (similar to line 731) if there's a bad value.

The failed case starts from line 471,
I just revise the condition to meet changes.
Sorry for description, line 471 above should be line 741
Just so I understand, why are we putting ADCs in PSUSensor?  Shouldn't they go into ADCSensor?
Not part of this patch, but there are two different ways to customize the scalefactor from baseConfig (line 873 and line 721)
Would you please to tell what should I add in line 873 and 721 as your expectation?
I am trying to understand the difference between the two ways to customize and which one you use and why.
not part of this patch, but this can be moved  into else {} of line 874
It sounds like another logical change, would you like to change them in a new seperate commit?
Yes, I am ok with leave it to a separate change
This now needs all the same checks you did on line 736
Done

Hi Ed & Delphine,

Sorry for update the patch without asking, because this patch is addressing the problem we are facing, but not been updated for few months.

I submit the new patchset to address Ed's comment, 
Please kindly have a review, thank you.
